00:00:31.040 --> 00:00:31.600
Oh, there it goes.

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:35.890
It's good to be in San Francisco,
and I am very pleased to have the

00:00:35.890 --> 00:00:39.420
opportunity to meet before you at
the Worldwide Developers Conference.

00:00:39.420 --> 00:00:44.300
It's a great opportunity for us
to explain these licensing terms,

00:00:44.300 --> 00:00:47.400
which have been the subject of
so much discussion in the press

00:00:47.700 --> 00:00:49.840
and privately and so forth.

00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:53.340
And certainly,
interest runs no higher among users

00:00:53.700 --> 00:00:57.960
of MPEG-4 technology than those
of you in this room and at this

00:00:58.300 --> 00:01:02.830
conference because of Apple's,
certainly, their great support through

00:01:03.030 --> 00:01:04.290
the QuickTime products.

00:01:04.340 --> 00:01:09.050
And obviously, that's very important to
the start of this market.

00:01:09.420 --> 00:01:14.720
The other element that is important
to the start of the market is

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:17.400
to clarify licensing terms.

00:01:17.650 --> 00:01:22.300
And I say that not only for
whatever needs to be done still now,

00:01:22.330 --> 00:01:28.590
but what needed to be done even a year
and a half ago when various controversies

00:01:28.700 --> 00:01:33.020
started over what this license was
about and what it wasn't about.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:39.300
The reason I say this as
a platform is because,

00:01:39.300 --> 00:01:41.890
you know,
to start out the discussion here,

00:01:41.930 --> 00:01:46.160
is because every
technology such as MPEG-4,

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:50.460
which is an open standard,
is subject to technology

00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:54.960
that is owned by many,
many different patent holders.

00:01:56.600 --> 00:02:01.140
And in the old days, I say the old days,
the days before standards

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:04.170
were widely implemented,
before digital video and

00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:08.100
digital audio and other digital
technologies were implemented,

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:15.230
users were pretty much on their own when
it came to clearing rights under relevant

00:02:15.230 --> 00:02:18.700
patents for the use of a technology.

00:02:19.810 --> 00:02:25.610
Picture the situation where, for example,
you as a user or other

00:02:25.610 --> 00:02:33.520
implementers of the technology
go forward with the technology,

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:33.520
or Apple, for that matter,
goes forward with the technology.

00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:38.400
and does not have the availability
of a license such as the one we

00:02:39.340 --> 00:02:43.160
present that provides access to
many different patents owned by many

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:46.470
different patent holders in one place.

00:02:46.940 --> 00:02:53.420
The consequence of that, unfortunately,
is that the implementer, the user,

00:02:53.420 --> 00:02:53.420
the promoter

00:02:53.730 --> 00:02:58.330
is subject to potential
infringement by 20,

00:02:58.500 --> 00:03:02.810
25, 30 different parties that may
own essential patent rights.

00:03:03.360 --> 00:03:06.400
So they go out with the technology,
and obviously there's a possibility

00:03:06.400 --> 00:03:09.590
of litigation or infringement
allegations and so forth.

00:03:09.660 --> 00:03:12.850
And that's what
MPEG LA tries to clear up.

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:18.710
That is the entire purpose of our being,
which is to try to bring as much of

00:03:18.710 --> 00:03:23.740
this essential intellectual property
rights under one license as possible,

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:27.150
so that when a user goes to market,
they don't have to have 20

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:31.740
negotiations or 25 or 30 negotiations
with individual patent holders.

00:03:32.680 --> 00:03:36.060
It doesn't take a brain scientist to
understand that a technology that has

00:03:36.060 --> 00:03:40.370
to go through that many negotiations is,
frankly, dead on arrival.

00:03:41.910 --> 00:03:45.950
So what we try to do is bring the 20
or 25 or 30 patent holders together

00:03:45.950 --> 00:03:49.880
under one license so that users
and implementers and promoters can

00:03:49.880 --> 00:03:53.920
get the rights they need in one
place with one negotiation and move

00:03:53.920 --> 00:03:59.010
forward from there without fear of
having infringement claims hoisted

00:03:59.010 --> 00:04:01.700
upon them by the patent owners.

00:04:02.090 --> 00:04:04.500
Some of what I've said may
seem kind of cloudy to you,

00:04:04.590 --> 00:04:06.830
so let me take it step by step,
give you a little

00:04:06.890 --> 00:04:10.730
background about MPEG LA,
and then let's talk specifically

00:04:11.090 --> 00:04:13.600
about the MPEG-4 Visual License.

00:04:13.600 --> 00:04:17.670
I did want to just set that up as
background though for the general role

00:04:17.670 --> 00:04:20.680
that MPEG LA plays in this technology.

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:27.720
We all know that.

00:04:27.860 --> 00:04:29.560
A lot has been said.

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:31.490
A lot has been written.

00:04:31.630 --> 00:04:34.520
I myself was a recipient
of probably 6,000 emails.

00:04:34.520 --> 00:04:38.180
Some of you in this room I'm hoping
I actually communicated with.

00:04:38.260 --> 00:04:39.910
We tried to respond to all of them.

00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:42.360
And by the way, they were very helpful.

00:04:43.110 --> 00:04:47.510
They made a tangible change in the
licensing terms as a result of what you

00:04:47.510 --> 00:04:52.180
wrote and what you expressed and the
heartfelt feelings that you had about

00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:56.970
the ease of implementation that you
faced or the difficulty of implementation

00:04:56.970 --> 00:04:59.510
you faced when the terms first came out.

00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:02.890
As you may know,
they were revised about six months later,

00:05:02.890 --> 00:05:04.790
reflecting many of your views.

00:05:04.820 --> 00:05:08.130
Obviously, not everyone is always
happy with licensing terms,

00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:11.010
but we went a long way, we think,
to correcting some of the

00:05:11.010 --> 00:05:12.940
deficiencies in the original license.

00:05:12.940 --> 00:05:19.530
That's what we're going to discuss.

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:26.680
As I said, first I'd like to provide
some background on MPEG LA.

00:05:26.770 --> 00:05:30.040
MPEG LA is not a patent holder.

00:05:30.150 --> 00:05:34.690
MPEG LA is not a user of any technology.

00:05:35.890 --> 00:05:41.060
In terms of promoting
it or being a licensee,

00:05:41.310 --> 00:05:44.570
shall I say,
of one of our own licensing programs.

00:05:44.570 --> 00:05:46.990
We are an independent company.

00:05:47.510 --> 00:05:53.130
whose sole purpose is to try to
bring order out of the market chaos.

00:05:53.130 --> 00:05:57.090
The market chaos is what
I referred to earlier.

00:05:57.090 --> 00:06:00.740
The situation where a
standard that everyone likes,

00:06:00.740 --> 00:06:04.940
many people want to use,
has one single problem that holds

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:07.000
it back from implementation.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:11.500
And that single problem is how can
we get it out there and get it widely

00:06:11.560 --> 00:06:18.200
used by the biggest number of users
without facing multiple infringement

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:21.760
actions or essential patent claims.

00:06:22.130 --> 00:06:26.210
So where we began was in 1997.

00:06:26.210 --> 00:06:28.540
As a company,
we began licensing the MPEG-2

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:31.280
video compression standard.

00:06:31.470 --> 00:06:33.320
That was our beginning.

00:06:34.270 --> 00:06:37.660
The single biggest challenge to
MPEG-2's adoption was dealing with the

00:06:37.660 --> 00:06:40.470
essential intellectual property rights.

00:06:41.610 --> 00:06:45.640
MPEG, as you know,
stands for Moving Pictures Expert Group.

00:06:45.670 --> 00:06:48.720
It was a group of engineers from
all over the world who still meet

00:06:48.970 --> 00:06:50.940
to discuss international standards.

00:06:50.970 --> 00:06:53.300
They are the authors
of the MPEG-4 standard.

00:06:53.330 --> 00:06:56.950
They were the authors
of the MPEG-2 standard.

00:06:57.140 --> 00:07:02.180
The standard was developed in
the early '90s to the mid '90s.

00:07:02.670 --> 00:07:09.230
It was an answer to where to begin with
a high quality digital compression for

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:14.700
real time video in the broadband sense,
in the broadcast sense, by satellite,

00:07:14.820 --> 00:07:18.080
by cable, and by DVD player.

00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:21.420
And as I said,
it was well known going into this

00:07:21.420 --> 00:07:25.140
process that the technology which
the MPEG group had put together

00:07:25.140 --> 00:07:29.460
as a single specification to be
made available widely to the world

00:07:29.990 --> 00:07:33.330
had one barrier to implementation,
one significant barrier

00:07:33.410 --> 00:07:34.520
to implementation.

00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:37.620
I think it's obvious to all
of you in this room what the

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:41.360
benefits of interoperability are,
which is what the purpose

00:07:41.370 --> 00:07:43.000
of these standards is.

00:07:43.210 --> 00:07:50.520
So the MPEG-2 standard sitting here
on a voluminous amount of paper.

00:07:50.630 --> 00:07:52.930
was no better than the paper
it was written on unless

00:07:52.950 --> 00:07:54.640
it could be implemented.

00:07:54.670 --> 00:07:58.100
And many companies throughout the
industry had a significant interest

00:07:58.140 --> 00:08:02.970
in seeing its implementation
because obviously that answered

00:08:02.980 --> 00:08:05.560
the problem to interoperability.

00:08:05.590 --> 00:08:10.880
But, many patents owned by many patent
owners caused potential for confusion,

00:08:10.900 --> 00:08:17.020
conflict, spelled litigation, and cost,
spelled multiple negotiations,

00:08:17.050 --> 00:08:21.100
and possibly endless negotiations,
and possibly negotiations

00:08:21.110 --> 00:08:24.680
that were inaccessible to
the normally sized company.

00:08:24.710 --> 00:08:27.360
You know, maybe large companies,
maybe companies,

00:08:27.370 --> 00:08:30.570
small companies with significant
technology would see the inside

00:08:30.670 --> 00:08:34.160
of the door of a particular patent
holder who wanted to cross license

00:08:34.160 --> 00:08:35.800
for that particular technology.

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:39.780
But in general,
in order to foster the widest

00:08:39.950 --> 00:08:43.510
possible use of this standard,
there had to be a different

00:08:43.510 --> 00:08:44.860
way of doing things.

00:08:45.500 --> 00:08:49.190
So the MPEG group set in
motion an intellectual

00:08:49.190 --> 00:08:50.980
property rights working group.

00:08:51.010 --> 00:08:56.560
It was headed by Baron Futa,
who is the current CEO of MPEG LA.

00:08:56.560 --> 00:09:01.000
They worked for a number of years
on coming up with a blueprint

00:09:01.730 --> 00:09:04.470
for overcoming this problem.

00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:09.300
The result of that deliberation
was the creation of MPEG LA.

00:09:09.400 --> 00:09:13.620
Of course, MPEG LA used that blueprint,
but as a private company,

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:17.850
had to sell patent holders on,
or shall I say convince patent

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:22.140
holders to include their intellectual
property under one license in a model

00:09:22.170 --> 00:09:24.360
that had never been tried before.

00:09:26.570 --> 00:09:28.540
This was unprecedented.

00:09:28.610 --> 00:09:32.820
The venture, which became the MPEG-2
Patent Portfolio License,

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:37.500
went before a six-month review
before the Department of Justice.

00:09:37.800 --> 00:09:43.800
As a matter of caution and common sense,
because it was new and unprecedented,

00:09:43.800 --> 00:09:48.610
and the Department of Justice in its
review found the business plan of

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:52.800
MPEG LA for MPEG-2 to be pro-competitive.

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:58.390
It was designed with many elements
in mind to achieve fairness,

00:09:58.450 --> 00:10:02.240
reasonableness, and nondiscrimination.

00:10:02.740 --> 00:10:06.400
Fairness and nondiscrimination
and reasonableness,

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:07.700
particularly important elements.

00:10:07.750 --> 00:10:11.140
You'll probably hear me
refer to them later today.

00:10:11.370 --> 00:10:11.980
They're big words.

00:10:12.060 --> 00:10:14.300
They don't mean much by themselves.

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:19.260
But we hope that our licenses and the
acceptance of those licenses in the

00:10:19.260 --> 00:10:23.660
market helps to define what is fair,
reasonable, and non-discriminatory

00:10:23.660 --> 00:10:24.900
in the marketplace.

00:10:24.990 --> 00:10:27.320
Obviously,
a license that is widely accepted

00:10:27.960 --> 00:10:30.490
can be viewed as fair and reasonable.

00:10:30.640 --> 00:10:34.300
We administer them to
be non-discriminatory.

00:10:34.340 --> 00:10:36.180
What does that mean?

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:40.240
Non-discriminatory means
that a patent holder,

00:10:40.240 --> 00:10:45.600
a licensor as we call them,
who happens also to be a licensee,

00:10:45.600 --> 00:10:49.090
a user of the technology,
and there are many,

00:10:49.860 --> 00:10:54.040
will be treated the same
as any other licensee.

00:10:54.080 --> 00:10:57.960
They receive no favorable
treatment over a licensee who

00:10:57.960 --> 00:11:00.450
does not have patents themselves.

00:11:01.870 --> 00:11:04.040
Very important principle.

00:11:04.040 --> 00:11:07.450
So not to pick on a particular company,
but if you go on our website

00:11:07.450 --> 00:11:11.570
you will see that there are
currently 22 patent holders in the

00:11:11.570 --> 00:11:14.030
MPEG-2 patent portfolio license.

00:11:17.140 --> 00:11:24.290
They include names such as Sony and
Matsushita and Columbia University.

00:11:24.350 --> 00:11:27.590
It's a wide spectrum of patent owners.

00:11:28.530 --> 00:11:31.660
And Columbia, of course,
is not a licensee because they don't use

00:11:31.710 --> 00:11:34.640
the technology in the conventional sense.

00:11:34.830 --> 00:11:38.880
But a Sony, for example,
pays the same royalty rates

00:11:39.050 --> 00:11:41.580
that any other user pays.

00:11:41.730 --> 00:11:45.860
Obviously, as a patent holder,
they get a piece of the revenue

00:11:45.860 --> 00:11:48.210
that comes as a result of any
royalties that are collected

00:11:48.710 --> 00:11:50.970
for the use of this technology.

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:55.880
But the technology was
not developed for free.

00:11:55.950 --> 00:11:58.600
It was not developed at no cost.

00:11:58.680 --> 00:12:04.200
This is their way of getting a return,
a reasonable return on their

00:12:04.200 --> 00:12:07.930
investment so that they,
like other patent holders,

00:12:07.970 --> 00:12:13.050
can continue to develop new
technologies that fuel the marketplace.

00:12:16.600 --> 00:12:21.460
Our sole business is based on what
we call one-stop patent licenses.

00:12:21.540 --> 00:12:24.300
Once again,
MPEG LA itself is not a patent holder.

00:12:24.430 --> 00:12:29.180
We aggregate essential patents owned
by many parties under one license.

00:12:29.180 --> 00:12:32.900
And then we have the right
to sub-license those to the

00:12:32.900 --> 00:12:36.140
marketplace on the same fair,
reasonable,

00:12:36.140 --> 00:12:39.340
non-discriminatory terms to everyone.

00:12:40.410 --> 00:12:42.660
We'll get into that more in a minute.

00:12:42.710 --> 00:12:49.810
I apologize if we spend this much
time on the background of MPEG LA,

00:12:49.810 --> 00:12:52.920
but I think it's important to try to
understand where we're coming from,

00:12:53.050 --> 00:12:55.990
what we're trying to achieve,
and I think it'll be easier to

00:12:55.990 --> 00:13:00.770
understand the MPEG-4 license once
we begin that discussion momentarily.

00:13:01.630 --> 00:13:05.510
This is the problem that
MPEG LA set out to solve.

00:13:05.730 --> 00:13:08.840
I won't review it all,
but suffice it to say

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:12.120
that in the last 10 years,

00:13:12.700 --> 00:13:17.540
Companies, individuals have understood,
like they never have before,

00:13:17.590 --> 00:13:20.080
the value of intellectual property.

00:13:22.050 --> 00:13:30.760
rapid patenting, voluminous applications
before the US Patent Office.

00:13:31.060 --> 00:13:35.040
I'm unprecedented in history in terms of
the number of patents that are entering

00:13:35.670 --> 00:13:37.000
the office and are being reviewed.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.260
I don't have the figures at hand,
but I understand that it's probably

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:41.790
doubled over the last 10-year period.

00:13:41.790 --> 00:13:47.890
It means that people are patenting

00:13:48.860 --> 00:13:51.830
Anything that they
believe to be patentable,

00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:55.990
something that is an invention which was
not subject to any prior publication and

00:13:55.990 --> 00:13:59.550
which they are the first to discover.

00:13:59.730 --> 00:14:02.880
What happens is that there's growing
interdependence among patents.

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:07.040
When you put out a standard
such as MPEG-2 or MPEG-4,

00:14:07.040 --> 00:14:12.080
it isn't just one invention like the
telephone and Alexander Graham Bell or

00:14:12.080 --> 00:14:15.600
the other poor guy who had
the real patent on that.

00:14:16.730 --> 00:14:21.490
But it is a situation where the
standard that is established is

00:14:21.900 --> 00:14:28.010
subject to many patents covering many
elements of the compression standard:

00:14:28.050 --> 00:14:33.700
the decoding, the encoding,
the transport, and all kinds of elements

00:14:33.700 --> 00:14:37.200
surrounding that,
whether it be spatial redundancy

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:39.980
or temporal redundancy or whatever.

00:14:40.200 --> 00:14:43.280
So there are many patents to deal with,
and it's not getting less.

00:14:43.320 --> 00:14:44.690
It's getting more.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.360
It's been referred to
as the patent thicket.

00:14:48.400 --> 00:14:52.040
And the result is that licensing
transaction costs for companies

00:14:52.130 --> 00:14:57.530
who engage in MPEG-2 or MPEG-4
or other such technologies are

00:14:57.530 --> 00:14:59.680
extraordinarily burdensome.

00:15:00.330 --> 00:15:04.260
The possibility that a technology
may do nothing except gather

00:15:04.490 --> 00:15:08.000
dust on the paper on which it
is written is greater than ever.

00:15:08.090 --> 00:15:11.790
There needs to be a bridge,
and the bridge is to try to set up a

00:15:11.790 --> 00:15:17.840
one-stop license as a transition to
the marketplace that can allow people

00:15:17.870 --> 00:15:23.460
to have non-discriminatory access to
the technology with one negotiation.

00:15:25.910 --> 00:15:29.980
One-on-one licensing arrangements
ruled the day before MPEG LA.

00:15:30.120 --> 00:15:31.220
That's the way people operated.

00:15:31.290 --> 00:15:33.000
They negotiated one-on-one.

00:15:33.110 --> 00:15:34.580
And they still negotiate one-on-one.

00:15:34.620 --> 00:15:39.270
MPEG LA does not replace
one-on-one licensing negotiations.

00:15:39.270 --> 00:15:43.440
It works with those that
are necessary in the market.

00:15:43.440 --> 00:15:46.900
It's one more element that technology
users have to choose from in

00:15:47.050 --> 00:15:51.390
determining how they want to deal with
their intellectual property rights.

00:15:53.280 --> 00:15:56.570
And I know I'm talking to a
group of knowledgeable people

00:15:56.720 --> 00:15:59.210
who do a lot of development.

00:15:59.450 --> 00:16:06.540
But basically,
the laws of most countries worldwide,

00:16:06.620 --> 00:16:09.300
virtually all,
recognize the right of an inventor

00:16:09.410 --> 00:16:12.510
to have the fruits of its invention.

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:17.470
And what that basically means is,
I always try to draw it like a boundary

00:16:17.520 --> 00:16:19.240
line of a piece of real estate.

00:16:19.240 --> 00:16:22.790
That basically means that
you carve out the four walls,

00:16:22.890 --> 00:16:26.630
the four corners,
the four boundary lines of a patent.

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:30.500
And if a user trespasses
on that property,

00:16:30.510 --> 00:16:35.850
then what the law says is that
the patent holder has the right to

00:16:35.950 --> 00:16:42.240
exclude that user from using that
technology on which they trespass.

00:16:42.800 --> 00:16:44.280
And that is the nature of a patent.

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:45.600
So they're out there.

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:47.070
They have to be dealt with.

00:16:47.070 --> 00:16:48.930
MPEG LA didn't make them.

00:16:48.930 --> 00:16:51.060
Obviously,
we're glad they're there because

00:16:51.060 --> 00:16:52.480
that is MPEG LA's business.

00:16:52.480 --> 00:16:54.200
I can't apologize for that.

00:16:54.250 --> 00:16:56.460
But we take the
marketplace as we found it,

00:16:56.490 --> 00:16:59.940
and we're trying to make it easier
for users to deal with that issue

00:16:59.940 --> 00:17:04.040
rather than have to go through
individual negotiations with each one.

00:17:09.210 --> 00:17:10.990
So this is the way we do it.

00:17:11.030 --> 00:17:12.250
We put them in one license.

